  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Statement.}\n\nThe hyperspherical zero-point vacuum axiom treats the primordial TZP vacuum as a coherent \\(S^3\\) state with no effective signal propagation before symmetry breaking.\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\n\nLet the vacuum carrier be modeled by the three-sphere\n\\[\n\\mathcal{V}_{\\mathrm{TZP}}\\cong S^3.\n\\]\nA maximally coherent vacuum phase is represented by a constant phase field\n\\[\n\\phi(x)=\\phi_0,\\qquad x\\in S^3.\n\\]\nSince the phase is constant, its intrinsic gradient vanishes:\n\\[\n\\nabla_{S^3}\\phi=0.\n\\]\nThe corresponding pre-differentiated propagation speed is taken to be\n\\[\nc_{\\mathrm{eff}}=0.\n\\]\nAfter perturbation, the first admissible departure from perfect coherence may be represented by\n\\[\n\\phi(x,t)=\\phi_0+\\varepsilon\\,Y_{\\ell m}(x)e^{i\\omega t}.\n\\]\n\n\\paragraph{Wolfram Form.}\n\\begin{verbatim}\nVTZP = Sphere[3];\nphi[x_] := phi0;\nGradS3[phi[x]] == 0;\nceff == 0;\nphiPerturbed[x_, t_] := phi0 + eps*Y[l, m][x]*Exp[I*omega*t];\n\\end{verbatim}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\n\nID 0228 establishes the vacuum as a hyperspherical coherent state. Signal, phase variation, and mode structure enter only after perturbation breaks the perfectly uniform \\(S^3\\) condition.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
